9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1163, L.D. 1745, “An Act to Stabilize
10 Residential Treatment Capacity for Children and Youth in Maine”
11 Amend the bill by inserting after the title and before the enacting clause the following:
12 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
13 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
14 Whereas, this legislation must take effect immediately to ensure that the data
15 collection required for reporting from the Department of Health and Human Services
16 begins as soon as possible and prior to 90 days after adjournment; and
17 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
18 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
19 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
20 therefore,'
21 Amend the bill by inserting after section 1 the following:
22 'Sec. 2. 34-B MRSA §15003, sub-§9, as amended by PL 2021, c. 191, §1, is further
23 amended to read:
24 9. Reports. The department shall report by January 1st of each year to the joint
25 standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over health and human services
26 matters on the following matters:
27 A. The operation of the program, including numbers of children and families served
28 and their residences by county; any waiting lists; the progress of the department in
29 implementing improvement strategies; and appeals procedures requested, held and
30 decided, including the results of decided appeals;
31 B. Initiatives in acquiring and using federal grant funding;
32 C. Barriers to improved delivery of care to children and their families and the progress
33 of the department in overcoming those barriers; and
